{{efn|name = "capitalization and punctuation"|Descartes wrote this phrase only once, in a posthumously published lesser-known work.<ref name="AT">{{Citation | editor-last1 = Adam | editor-first1 = Charles | editor-last2 = Tannery | editor-first2 = Paul | author-link = René Descartes | contribution = La Recherche de la Vérité par La Lumiere Naturale | title = ''Oeuvres de Descartes'' | volume = X | year = 1901 | page = 535 | contribution-url = https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Descartes_-_Œuvres,_éd._Adam_et_Tannery,_X.djvu/535}}</ref>

It appeared there mid-sentence, uncapitalized, and with a comma. (Commas were not used in [[classical Latin]] but were a regular feature of scholastic Latin. Most modern reference works show it with a comma, but it is often presented without a comma in academic work and in popular usage.)

In the primary source, Descartes's [[Principles of Philosophy|''Principia Philosophiae'']], the proposition appears as '''''ego cogito, ergo sum'''''.<ref name="Descartes1644">{{cite book|author=Descartes, René |title=Principia Philosophiae |publisher=apud Ludovicum Elzevirium |url=https://archive.org/details/ita-bnc-mag-00001403-001 |quote=“Ego Cogito ergo sum”. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/ita-bnc-mag-00001403-001/page/n68 30], 31 |year=1644}}</ref>

